%N A389282 Total sum of lengths of the longest decreasing sequences in heapable permutations of length n.
%C A389282 A permutation [1...n] is heapable if it can be sequentially inserted into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A389282 The longest decreasing subsequence (LDS) of a heapable permutation is a subsequence of the given sequence in which the elements are in strictly decreasing order and the subsequence is as long as possible.
%H A389282 Benjamin Chen, Michael Cho, Mario Tutuncu-Macias, and Tony Tzolov, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dam.2023.01.025">Efficient methods of calculating the number of heapable permutations</a>, Discrete Applied Mathematics Volume 331, 31 May 2023, Pages 126-137.
%H A389282 Manolopoulos Panagiotis, <a href="/A389282/a389282.py.txt">Python Program</a>
%F A389282 a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} k*A390146(n,k).
%e A389282 For n=4 the heapable permutations and their LDS lengths:
%e A389282   (1,2,3,4): LDS=1 (no decreasing pair).
%e A389282   (1,3,2,4): LDS=2 (subsequence 3,2).
%e A389282   (1,2,4,3): LDS=2 (subsequence 4,3).
%e A389282   (1,4,2,3): LDS=2 (subsequence 4,2).
%e A389282   (1,3,4,2): LDS=2 (subsequence 4,2).
%e A389282 So the total LDS-sum is 1*1+2*4=9.
